A final-year medical student of Lagos State University (LASU), Adewunmi Akingbola, has recorded two remarkable feats. He was recently announced as a recipient of the Diana Award. This award was established in memory of Diana, Princess of Wales. The Diana Award is the most prestigious accolade a young person aged 9-25 years can receive for their social actions or humanitarian works.   Knocks for Fed Govt on new private varsities     LASU to tackle indecent dressing     After report, physically challenged Corps member gets job…   Adewunmi also emerged finalist of the Dalai Lama Fellowship — a program for social change agents working to solve problems inherent in their local communities and serves to help them incorporate contemplative leadership into their change-making journey. He has over the years been a recipient of several local and global recognitions and awards. Some of his awards include: the Clinton Global Initiative University which is an initiative of United States ex-President Bill Clinton, HSENation AfriSAFE Community Hero award; Africa 25 Under 25 Young leaders by iKapture Network and OportunityDesk; nominee top 100 Outstanding Young Persons in Nigeria by Junior Chamber International. All of these awards and recognitions were given based on Adewunmi’s changemaking projects in tackling the menace of Hepatitis in Nigeria through an initiative he founded, HealthDrive Nigeria. Adewunmi and his team creates awareness about the dreadful disease, conduct free Hepatitis B screening and helps residents of under-resourced communities gain access to affordable Hepatitis B vaccines. Armed with all of these remarkable feats, Adewunmi hopes that his story would inspire more young people like him to take up their reins of leadership to champion social impact projects to tackle current and emerging problems in their communities